{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17530436","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17530436"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:06:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:06:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14543"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14543","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14543"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.58,0.04,0.14,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7236"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56783"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7236","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7236"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14543"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42236"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"675"},{"type":"tags","id":"1238"},{"type":"tags","id":"4724"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17580"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35103"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35104"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56783","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/56783"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a text message informing him that his recent sexual partner has been diagnosed with syphilis. He reports that they had unprotected intercourse two weeks ago. He identifies as queer, and is unsure how many sexual partners he has had in the past six months as he regularly attends group-sex parties and often engages in unprotected sex. He has no significant medical history and takes HIV PrEP. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are no visible lesions or rashes on his skin or mucous membranes. You refer him for syphilis serological testing.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Wait for serological test results before starting treatment","Administer a single dose of intramuscular benzathine penicillin G","Advise the patient to monitor for symptoms and return if they develop","Refer the patient to a sexual health clinic","Prescribe oral doxycycline for two weeks"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this scenario, the patient has had recent sexual contact with a partner diagnosed with syphilis. The likelihood of syphilis transmission per act of unprotected intercourse in early syphilis is greater than 20%. In terms of contact tracing, this is considered high and presumptive treatment of any sexual contacts of a diagnosed patient is recommended. A \u003Cstrong\u003Esingle dose of intramuscular benzathine penicillin G \u003C/strong\u003Eis the recommended treatment. This approach helps prevent the development of syphilis in the patient and reduces the risk of further transmission, especially given the patient\u0027s regular engagement in group-sex.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWaiting for \u003Cstrong\u003Eserological test results\u003C/strong\u003E before starting treatment is not advisable in this case, as it could delay necessary intervention and increase the risk of disease progression. This patient is still within the window period of testing, so serological tests may be negative even if the patient has contracted syphilis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral doxycycline\u003C/strong\u003E is an alternative treatment for syphilis in patients who are allergic to penicillin, but it is not the first-line treatment in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdvising the patient to \u003Cstrong\u003Emonitor for symptoms\u003C/strong\u003E and return if they develop is not sufficient, as syphilis can be asymptomatic in its early stages, and delaying treatment could lead to complications. Moreover, given the high transmission rate, this approach would leave the patient at significant risk of infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EReferral to a \u003Cstrong\u003Esexual health clinic\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary at this stage, as the management of recent contact with syphilis is straightforward and can be handled in the general practice setting with presumptive treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Presumptive treatment for syphilis is recommended for individuals who have had recent sexual contact with a partner diagnosed with early syphilis.","Early treatment can prevent the progression of syphilis and reduce the risk of transmission.","The rate of transmission of early syphilis is \u003E20% per act of unprotected intercourse."],"references":["Stoltey JE, Cohen SE. Syphilis transmission: a review of the current evidence. Sexual Health [Internet]. 2015;12(2):103. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5973824/","SYPHILIS - Contact Tracing [Internet]. Contact Tracing. 2022. Available at: https://contacttracing.ashm.org.au/syphilis/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42236"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14543"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42236","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42236"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-21T22:09:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-21T22:15:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7236"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"quest